<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-447-493  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 447 493.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  Sept 17 1990 v1 n17 p11(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>1-2-3 release 3.1: Lotus announces immediate availability. (LotusDevelopment Corp.) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 3.1 (Spreadsheet software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSpreadsheetsWYSIWYG.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Lotus Development Corp. Monday announced the immediate availability of 1-2-3Release 3.1.andM;The new spreadsheet is a major upgrade to 1-2-3 that provides a WYSIWYG(What-You-See-Is-What-You- Get) graphical environment.andM;Designed for users who need to easily organize, analyze, and presentspreadsheet information, 1-2-3 Release 3.1 supports DOS and DOS with Windows3.0.andM;Lotus is supporting the 1-2-3 Release 3.1 product launch with an aggressiveadvertising and promotional campaign.andP;  This campaign includes a new programthat enables users to upgrade instantly at participating computer retailstores.andM;Within the graphical environment of 1-2-3 Release 3.1, users can perform allspreadsheet operations using either the keyboard or the mouse, withoutleaving the familiar 1-2-3 program.andP;  This includes the ability to modify orenter spreadsheet information, add color, change fonts, and printpresentation-quality output.andM;Marty Fahey, director of marketing for Lotus' PC spreadsheets.andM;Lotus will be aggressively marketing Release 3.1 with a multimillion dollaradvertising and promotional campaign aimed at reaching millions of potentialupgraders and new users in the coming months.andM;1-2-3 Release 3.1 is compatible with Windows 3.0, and includes a file thatautomatically configures the product for use with Windows 3.0.andP;  Users canlaunch Release 3.1 by clicking on an icon from the Windows desktop, transferdata between applications through the Windows clipboard, and run theirapplication in a sizable window with a text display.andP;  When operating underWindows 3.0 386/Enhanced mode, 1-2-3 Release 3.1 uses Windows memorymanagement facilities, allowing 1-2-3 users to take advantage oftask-switching capabilities.andM;NEW MEMORY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM 1-2-3 Release 3.1 offers a combination ofanalytic tools, and the widest range of publishing and presentation featuresfound in any spreadsheet available today, according to Lotus.andM;1-2-3 Release 3.1 enables users to: automatically compress print to fit on asingle page; use more than 96 type styles in a single worksheet; set dropshadows in a single step; use a built-in mini word processor; choose graphcolors from a palette of 224 colors and hatching patterns; view paginationdirectly on the worksheet; format multiple worksheets simultaneously; andautomatically wrap text around a graph.andM;In addition, 1-2-3 Release 3.1 provides a set of tools for enabling users tomore easily access and analyze data, using spreadsheet technologies providedonly by Lotus.andP;  These include: DataLens external data access; advancedrelational database capabilities; and application development tools via theLotus Add-in Toolkit.andM;The product's new virtual memory management system enables users to allocatean area of their hard disk as workspace, making it possible to create largerspreadsheets in less memory.andP;  In addition, the product's compatibility with awider range of PC AT compatibles should ease software installation andconfiguration.andM;SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS, PRICING, AND UPGRADES 1-2-3 Release 3.1 requires an IBMPC AT, PS/2, Compaq or compatible (with an 80286 or higher microprocessor), ahard disk, one megabyte of available system RAM, and DOS 3.0 or higher.andM;The suggested retail price of the 1-2-3 Release 3.1 Standard Edition is $595.andO;The network Server and Node Editions of the product will be available in thefourth quarter of 1990 at a suggested retail price of $795 and $495,respectively.andM;All customers who purchased 1-2-3 Release 3.0 before May 7, 1990, may upgradeto Release 3.1 for $35.andP;  Users who buy or have bought 1-2-3 Release 3.0 on orafter May 7, 1990, are entitled to a free upgrade to Release 3.1 throughDecember 31, 1990.andP;  1-2-3 Release 2.2 users may upgrade for a suggestedretail price of $75 through December 31, 1990.andP;  Users of 1-2-3 Releases 1,1A, 2, and 2.01 may upgrade to 1-2-3 Release 3.1 for a suggested retail priceof $150.andM;Registered users of 1-2-3 Release 3.1 automatically receive six months ofunlimited, toll-free access to Lotus' 1-2-3 support specialists, 24 hours aday, seven days a week.andP;  At the end of six months, users may elect tocontinue premium support, or use the company's standard support service.andM;NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL USERS: 1-2-3 Release 3.1 has been customized to meetthe language-specific needs of international markets, and provides for theeasy exchange of data and files between users in different countries.andP;  Inaddition to the U.S.andP;  English version, Lotus is also shipping theInternational English version of 1-2-3 Release 3.1, for distribution inoverseas markets.andP;  Fully translated versions of the product will also beavailable in French and German later this month.andP;  Swedish, Italian, Spanish,Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, and Portuguese versions will be available laterthis year.andM;All prices and terms are for the U.S.A.andP;  only.andO;</TEXT></DOC>